Command-line arguments are values passed to the script when it starts.
$0=script name
$1= first argument
$2 = sec
$# =number of argument
"$@" keeps each argument separate.
"$*" combines all arguments into a single string.
$? stores the exit status of the previously executed command. A value of 0 indicates success, while any non-zero value indicates an error.

#!/bin/bash

echo "Script Name : $0"
echo "First Argument : $1"
echo "Second Argument : $2"
echo "Number of Arguments : $#"
echo "All Arguments : $@"
echo "Current Script PID : $$"
